<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="49" pageId="2" pageNumber="48" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1438,1748,2007]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1436,152,255]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="49" pageId="2" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,318,1826,1852]" pageId="2" pageNumber="48">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[333,547,1827,1852]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Medetera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varvara">
<emphasis box="[333,547,1827,1852]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="48">Medetera varvara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is related to Egyptian 
<taxonomicName authority="Parent" authorityName="Parent" authorityYear="1878" box="[817,1074,1826,1852]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Oligochaetus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albescens">
<emphasis box="[817,841,1827,1852]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="48">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[857,972,1827,1852]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="48">albescens</emphasis>
(Parent)
</taxonomicName>
which differs from the former by silvery-white frons and face, hind coxa bearing three outer setae and fore tarsus unmodified. Ornamentation of fore legs is unknown for other species of Palearctic 
<taxonomicName box="[968,1080,1904,1929]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Medetera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[968,1080,1904,1929]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="48">Medetera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
including 
<taxonomicName authority="Mik, 1878" authorityName="Mik" authorityYear="1878" box="[1205,1358,1904,1930]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Oligochaetus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albescens">
<emphasis box="[1205,1229,1904,1929]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="48">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1244,1358,1904,1929]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="48">albescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which was published with a rather detailed description. In the Afrotropics, only 
<taxonomicName authority="Parent, 1936" authorityName="Parent" authorityYear="1936" box="[1020,1363,1942,1968]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Medetera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteoscutata">
<emphasis box="[1020,1203,1943,1968]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="48">M. luteoscutata</emphasis>
Parent, 
<number box="[1301,1363,1942,1968]" pageId="2" pageNumber="48" value="1936.0">1936</number>
</taxonomicName>
, has a small apicoventral process on tarsomere 
<number box="[628,643,1981,2007]" pageId="2" pageNumber="48" value="1.0">1</number>
and 
<number box="[700,714,1981,2007]" pageId="2" pageNumber="48" value="3.0">3</number>
of fore leg. Mainly Pantropical 
<taxonomicName authority="Becker, 1914" authorityName="Becker" authorityYear="1914" box="[1092,1431,1981,2007]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Saccopheronta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1092,1267,1981,2006]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="48">Saccopheronta</emphasis>
Becker, 
<number box="[1370,1431,1981,2007]" pageId="2" pageNumber="48" value="1914.0">1914</number>
</taxonomicName>
, a sister genus (
<bibRefCitation author="Grichanov" box="[334,551,152,178]" pageId="3" pageNumber="51" refString="Grichanov, I. Ya. (1997 b) Four new species of Saccopheronta Becker (Diptera: Dolichopodidae) from Tropical Africa with notes on the world fauna of the genus. International Journal of Dipterological Research, 8 (3), 123 - 134." type="journal article" year="1997" yearSuffix="b">
Grichanov 
<number box="[473,535,152,178]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" value="1997.0">1997</number>
b
</bibRefCitation>
) or “ 
<taxonomicName box="[615,725,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Medetera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aberrans">
<emphasis box="[615,725,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="49">aberrans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ group of 
<taxonomicName box="[858,975,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Medetera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[858,975,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="49">Medetera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<bibRefCitation author="Bickel" box="[1087,1242,152,178]" pageId="3" pageNumber="51" refString="Bickel, D. J. (1985) A revision of the Nearctic Medetera (Diptera: Dolichopodidae). United States Department of Agriculture Technical Bulletin, 1692, 1 - 109." type="journal article" year="1985">Bickel 1985</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Bickel" box="[1255,1317,152,178]" pageId="3" pageNumber="51" refString="Bickel, D. J. (1987) A Revision of the Oriental and Australasian Medetera (Diptera: Dolichopodidae). Records of the Australian Museum, 39, 131 - 182." type="journal article" year="1987">1987</bibRefCitation>
) includes species with thickened or widened tarsomeres 
<number box="[703,718,190,216]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" value="2.0">2</number>
and 
<number box="[777,792,190,216]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" value="3.0">3</number>
of male fore leg. The absolute majority of medeterine species of the world fauna have no remarkable fore leg decoration.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
